<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n47140f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n47" href="#n47140f">N47 (VI.B.40)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n47all.htm#n47140f"> 140(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ba</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">3. The <i>ba</i> <font color="green">[image]</font>, or heart-soul, was in some way connected with the <i>ka</i> &hellip; it is depicted as a human-headed hawk &hellip; it is seen in this form flying down the funeral pit, bearing air and food to the mummified body to which it belongs. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD3" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD3"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd Ed (1909) lx [The constituent parts of man physically, mentally, and spiritually]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
